
Slicing and Indexing

mystring = "Jyoti Aneja"
mystring[2:]  o: oti Aneja

mystring[:3] = Jyo

mystring[6] = A

String Properties/ Methos

Formatting with {} :

print('This is a string {}'.format('INSERTED'))

10/11/2020

name = 'Jyoti'
print('Hello, his name is {}'.format(name))

Using f string literals:

print(f'Hello, his name is {name}')


Formatting with placeholders:
print("I'm going to inject %s here." %'something')

x,y = 'some', 'more'
print("I'm going to inject %s text here and, %s text here."%(x,y))

Print formatting here: https://pyformat.info/

Lists:

Ordered sequences.

Dictionaries in Python:

Dictionaries are objects retrieved by key name. 
Unordered and can't be sorted.


Lists: Objects retrieved by location. Ordered sequence, can be indexed or sliced.

Tuples:

Tuples are very similar to lists. One key difference- immutability. 
Once an element is inside a tuple, it cannot be reassigned. Tuples use parenthesis: (1,2,3)


Sets:

Unordered collections of unique elements.
there can be one representative of the same object.

Booleans:

convey True/False

control flow & logic.































































